{{Orphan|date=November 2015}}
An {{nihongo|'''alibi-ya'''|アリバイ屋|aribai ya}} is a kind of business in [[Japan]] that creates an identity viewed as socially respectable for peoples involved in occupations viewed as shameful, typically identities for women involved in the [[sex industry]].<ref name="NY Times - 11Jul199 - In Japan, Alibis Are An Industry">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/07/11/weekinreview/in-japan-alibis-are-an-industry.html|title=In Japan, Alibis Are An Industry|last=Kristof|first=Nicholas D.|date=July 11, 1999|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=21 May 2012}}</ref> The fictitious identity is created to conceal the person's actual from her family, and potential spouses. Services provided by alibi-ya range from simply a phone answering services at a non-existent employer to arrangements for a boss to give a speech at the client's wedding praising her work at the non-existent company.<ref name="ABC News - 21May2012 - Japanese sex workers sold fictitious lives">{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-05-21/businesses-sell-alibis-to-japanese-sex-workers/4023420|title=Japanese sex workers sold fictitious lives|last=Willacy|first=Mark|date=21 May 2012|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=21 May 2012}}</ref> Though the business is not illegal of itself, alibi-ya came to attention in 2011 when fake documents issued by an alibi-ya were used to illegally obtain bank loans.<ref name="ABC News - 21May2012 - Japanese sex workers sold fictitious lives"/><ref name="Nikkei BP - 10May2011 - The fraud called 'alibi-ya' a useful tool">{{cite news|url=http://www.nikkeibp.co.jp/article/sj/20111004/286173/?P=2&ST=rebuild|title=The fraud called 'alibi-ya' a useful tool|last=Natsuhara|first=Takeshi|date=10 May 2011|work=[[Nikkei Business Publications|Nikkei BP]]|publisher=[[Nihon Keizai Shimbun]]|accessdate=21 May 2012}}</ref>
==Etymology== "Alibi-ya" is a combination of the [[English language|English]] world "[[alibi]]" and the [[Japanese language|Japanese]] "[[wikt:屋#Japanese|ya]]", meaning "shop" or "seller".<ref name="NY Times - 11Jul199 - In Japan, Alibis Are An Industry"/> It is also written in Japanese as {{nihongo|aribai-gaisha|アリバイ会社}}, meaning "alibi [[Wikt:会社|company]]".<ref name="Nikkei BP - 10May2011 - The fraud called 'alibi-ya' a useful tool"/>
